Conclusion
Vitamin D (50,000 IU/week) and magnesium (6 mg/kg/
day) co-supplementation for a duration of 8-weeks could
improve the behavioral function and mental health in chil-
dren with ADHD affected with low serum level of vitamin
D and magnesium. However, further well-designed studies
with larger sample sizes are needed to validate our find-
ings and determine whether vitamin D and magnesium
deficiency are the results of ADHD or whether they are
risk factors for this disorder.
